diff --git a/blog/best-time-to-start-laser-mumbai.html b/blog/best-time-to-start-laser-mumbai.html
index fd9a7a8..a1a7f69 100644
--- a/blog/best-time-to-start-laser-mumbai.html
+++ b/blog/best-time-to-start-laser-mumbai.html
@@ -206,16 +206,16 @@
 <p>Mumbai's weather runs three big cycles — monsoon, humid summer, and pleasant winter. Which is the best time to start laser hair removal? Here's the honest answer.</p>
 
 <h2>The Simple Rule: Avoid Fresh Tan</h2>
-<p>Laser treats untanned skin best. Any period where your skin has recently been tanned or sunburnt is not ideal for starting laser. This means:</p>
+<p>Laser treats untanned skin best. In a long-term study of alexandrite laser hair removal across Fitzpatrick skin types I-V, the best hair-reduction outcomes were reported in untanned patients, with tanned or recently sun-exposed skin carrying a higher chance of transient pigment changes (Eremia et al., 2001). Any period where your skin has recently been tanned or sunburnt is not ideal for starting laser. This means:</p>
 
 <h2>Best Season: October to March (Winter/Post-Monsoon)</h2>
-<p>This is the ideal window in Mumbai. Skin is at its natural baseline colour, sun exposure is manageable, and you'll complete most of a 6-session course before summer's sun peaks. Weather is comfortable for post-session recovery.</p>
+<p>This is the ideal window in Mumbai. Skin is at its natural baseline colour, sun exposure is manageable, and you'll complete most of a treatment course — typically spaced four to six weeks apart to match the hair growth cycle (Eremia et al., 2001) — before summer's sun peaks. Weather is comfortable for post-session recovery.</p>
 
 <h2>Second Best: Late Monsoon (August–September)</h2>
 <p>Once monsoon settles in, skin is often untanned and hydrated. If you start in August, you'll finish most sessions by February. The tricky part: humidity can make post-session aftercare feel less pleasant.</p>
 
 <h2>Trickier: Peak Summer (April–June)</h2>
-<p>Not ideal. Skin often has fresh tan from unavoidable sun exposure. Post-session sun protection is harder in extreme heat. It's still possible — just requires strict SPF discipline.</p>
+<p>Not ideal. Skin often has fresh tan from unavoidable sun exposure, and the extra melanin a tan adds to the epidermis competes with the hair follicle for laser energy — the same reason clinicians treating naturally darker skin (Fitzpatrick IV-VI) favour longer wavelengths and more conservative settings (Fayne et al., 2018). Post-session sun protection is harder in extreme heat. It's still possible — just requires strict SPF discipline.</p>
 
 <h2>Also Possible: Peak Monsoon (June–July)</h2>
 <p>Skin is often untanned, but constant humidity can slow post-session healing. If you're disciplined about aftercare, this can work. Bonus: dressing in loose clothes is comfortable post-session.</p>
