diff --git a/blog/cellulite-treatment-what-works.html b/blog/cellulite-treatment-what-works.html
index 99b3a04..aa80c8c 100644
--- a/blog/cellulite-treatment-what-works.html
+++ b/blog/cellulite-treatment-what-works.html
@@ -203,16 +203,16 @@
         </figure>
 
         <div class="blog-post__content">
-<p>Cellulite affects 80–90% of women, regardless of weight or fitness. It's not a fat problem — it's a structural skin problem. The market is flooded with treatments claiming to cure it. Here's the honest ranking of what actually works.</p>
+<p>Cellulite affects an estimated 80–90% of women, regardless of weight or fitness (Pavicic et al., 2006). It's not primarily a fat problem — dermatology reviews describe it as a structural change in the skin's connective tissue, driven mainly by the fibrous septae beneath the surface (Bass et al., 2023). The market is flooded with treatments claiming to cure it. Here's the honest ranking of what actually works.</p>
 
 <h2>What Cellulite Actually Is</h2>
-<p>Cellulite is dimpled skin caused by fibrous bands (septae) pulling down on skin while fat pushes up. The dimpling is what you see. It's largely genetic and hormonal — even thin, athletic women get cellulite.</p>
+<p>Cellulite is dimpled skin caused by fibrous bands (septae) pulling down on skin while fat pushes up. The dimpling is what you see. It's largely genetic and hormonal — female sex, increasing age, and body composition all contribute to its severity, according to a review in <em>Dermatologic Surgery</em> (Bass et al., 2023) — which is why even thin, athletic women get cellulite.</p>
 
 <h2>The Honest Truth</h2>
-<p>No treatment fully eliminates cellulite. But several treatments reduce its appearance significantly. Realistic expectation: 40–60% improvement, not 100% clearance.</p>
+<p>No treatment fully eliminates cellulite. A 2023 clinical review in <em>Aesthetic Plastic Surgery</em> proposes matching treatment intensity to severity — lifestyle and topicals for mild cellulite, noninvasive devices for moderate, and minimally invasive procedures for severe — rather than expecting any single option to deliver full clearance (Menon et al., 2023). Realistic expectation: meaningful improvement in appearance, not 100% clearance.</p>
 
 <h2>Tier 1: Actually Works — Jordi Shape (Vacuum + RF + LED)</h2>
-<p><a href="/services/jordi-shape">Jordi Shape</a> uses rotational vacuum + radiofrequency + LED. The vacuum loosens fibrous bands, RF stimulates collagen, LED supports skin quality. 6–8 sessions delivers visible smoothing of dimpling. Best current option for cellulite.</p>
+<p><a href="/services/jordi-shape">Jordi Shape</a> uses rotational vacuum + radiofrequency + LED. The vacuum loosens fibrous bands, RF stimulates collagen, LED supports skin quality. Among noninvasive options, radiofrequency-based devices show the strongest efficacy in current peer-reviewed literature (Menon et al., 2023), and a review of vacuum-assisted RF systems reported an average 55% improvement in cellulite appearance across treated areas (Belenky et al., 2012). 6–8 sessions delivers visible smoothing of dimpling. Best current option for cellulite.</p>
 
 <h2>Tier 2: Also Works — MNRF (RF Micro-Needling)</h2>
 <p><a href="/services/mnrf">MNRF</a> tightens skin and boosts collagen. Works well on cellulite-affected areas by improving skin quality. Complements Jordi Shape.</p>
@@ -224,7 +224,7 @@
 <p>Deep tissue and lymphatic drainage massage temporarily improves cellulite appearance for a few days. Not a long-term solution but pleasant and helpful before an event.</p>
 
 <h2>Tier 5: Marginal — Topical Creams</h2>
-<p>Caffeine-based creams temporarily tighten skin for hours. Retinoid creams may help long-term with consistent use. Neither delivers dramatic results.</p>
+<p>Caffeine-based creams temporarily tighten skin for hours — caffeine cream is one of the few topical ingredients described as having an actual evidence base for cellulite, alongside retinol (Pavicic et al., 2006). Retinoid creams may help more gradually: a placebo-controlled trial found six months of twice-daily topical retinol increased skin elasticity by roughly 11% at treated sites, though it did little to smooth out the visible dimpling itself (Piérard-Franchimont et al., 2000). Neither delivers dramatic results.</p>
 
 <h2>Not Recommended</h2>
 <p>Injection treatments claiming "cellulite dissolving" — evidence is thin. Aggressive body lasers marketed for cellulite — often expensive with limited benefit. "Detox" wraps and lymphatic drainage machines at spas — temporary depuffing only.</p>
