diff --git a/blog/chemical-peels-for-indian-skin.html b/blog/chemical-peels-for-indian-skin.html
index 97f8e97..377e115 100644
--- a/blog/chemical-peels-for-indian-skin.html
+++ b/blog/chemical-peels-for-indian-skin.html
@@ -206,19 +206,19 @@
 <p>Chemical peels are one of the most misunderstood treatments for Indian skin. When done right, they're incredibly effective. When done wrong — with the wrong strength or the wrong peel — they cause pigmentation that's harder to fix than the original problem. Here's what you should know.</p>
 
 <h2>Why Indian Skin is Different</h2>
-<p>Indian skin has more active melanocytes (pigment-producing cells) than lighter skin tones. Inflammation triggers pigment, which is why the wrong peel causes darkening. But controlled, dermatologist-designed peels work brilliantly on Indian skin — often better than lasers for certain concerns.</p>
+<p>Indian skin generally carries a higher density of active, UV-responsive melanocytes than lighter skin tones — the same phototype-related trait that makes darker skin more prone to post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH) after any inflammatory insult, not just from peels but from acne, waxing, or sun exposure (Chan et al., 2018). Inflammation triggers pigment, which is why the wrong peel causes darkening. But controlled, dermatologist-designed peels work brilliantly on Indian skin — often better than lasers for certain concerns — and published safety data on peels specifically in darker racial-ethnic groups back this up (Grimes, 1999).</p>
 
 <h2>Peel Types Safe for Indian Skin</h2>
-<p>Glycolic acid (30–70%), salicylic acid (20–30%), lactic acid, mandelic acid, azelaic acid, TCA (10–20% for medium peels), and combination peels formulated for darker skin. Modified Jessner's peel is another option for pigmentation.</p>
+<p>Glycolic acid (30–70%), salicylic acid (20–30% — a concentration shown to be both safe and effective in Fitzpatrick V–VI skin, including for treating existing post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation (Grimes, 1999)), lactic acid, mandelic acid, azelaic acid, TCA (10–20% for medium peels), and combination peels formulated for darker skin. Salicylic-mandelic combination peels in particular have shown efficacy and tolerability comparable to glycolic acid peels in Indian melasma patients (Sarkar et al., 2016). Modified Jessner's peel is another option for pigmentation.</p>
 
 <h2>Peel Types to Avoid</h2>
-<p>Phenol peels (too strong for Indian skin), high-strength TCA (>25%) without dermatologist supervision, unknown "at-home" peels, and salon peels of unclear strength or ingredient.</p>
+<p>Phenol peels (too strong for Indian skin), high-strength TCA (>25%) without dermatologist supervision — in a head-to-head comparison of peeling agents in skin-of-color melasma patients, TCA peels produced more adverse effects than glycolic or lactic acid peels used on the same schedule (Sahu &amp; Dayal, 2021) — unknown "at-home" peels, and salon peels of unclear strength or ingredient.</p>
 
 <h2>What Peels Actually Do</h2>
 <p>They exfoliate the top layers of skin, triggering renewal underneath. Deeper peels reach the pigment layer. The result: fresher, brighter, more even skin over a course of sessions.</p>
 
 <h2>Best Peels by Concern</h2>
-<p>Melasma & sun damage: TCA + glycolic combination, 4–6 sessions. Acne: salicylic peels, 4–6 sessions. Dullness: glycolic peels, quarterly. Fine lines: mandelic peels, monthly.</p>
+<p>Melasma & sun damage: TCA + glycolic combination, 4–6 sessions — glycolic and salicylic-mandelic peels have both produced significant, well-tolerated improvement in Indian melasma patients over a comparable course (Sarkar et al., 2016). Acne: salicylic peels, 4–6 sessions, a modality an evidence-based review of Asian populations found effective and safe for acne and acne scarring even in darker skin types (Handog et al., 2012). Dullness: glycolic peels, quarterly. Fine lines: mandelic peels, monthly.</p>
 
 <h2>What to Expect</h2>
 <p>Superficial peels: no visible peeling, mild flaking. Medium peels: 2–5 days of peeling, redness. All peels: temporarily sensitive skin, essential daily SPF 50+.</p>
