diff --git a/blog/cryolipolysis-complete-guide.html b/blog/cryolipolysis-complete-guide.html
index d580636..b35be69 100644
--- a/blog/cryolipolysis-complete-guide.html
+++ b/blog/cryolipolysis-complete-guide.html
@@ -179,9 +179,9 @@
 
         <h2>The Science Behind Fat Freezing</h2>
 
-        <p>Fat cells, or adipocytes, crystallise at higher temperatures than the cells that make up your skin, muscles, and nerves. During a cryolipolysis session, the applicator cools the treatment area to a temperature that triggers crystallisation within the fat cells while leaving surrounding tissue completely unharmed.</p>
+        <p>Fat cells, or adipocytes, crystallise at higher temperatures than the cells that make up your skin, muscles, and nerves. During a cryolipolysis session, the applicator cools the treatment area to a temperature that triggers crystallisation within the fat cells while leaving surrounding tissue completely unharmed. This selective sensitivity was first demonstrated in the foundational pre-clinical research behind cryolipolysis, which found that controlled local cooling produced a lobular panniculitis and gradual, months-long loss of subcutaneous fat with no clinical or histological evidence of injury to the overlying skin (Manstein et al., 2008).</p>
 
-        <p>Once crystallised, these fat cells undergo apoptosis -- a natural process of programmed cell death. Over the following weeks, your body's lymphatic system identifies these dead cells, breaks them down, and eliminates them naturally through your liver. The process is gradual and controlled, which is why results appear progressively rather than overnight.</p>
+        <p>Once crystallised, these fat cells become injured and are gradually cleared. Over the following weeks, your body's natural inflammatory and lymphatic processes identify these damaged cells and metabolise the released lipids the way it processes fat from any other source. The process is gradual and controlled, which is why results appear progressively rather than overnight.</p>
 
         <p>Here is the most important part: once fat cells are destroyed, they do not regenerate. Adults have a fixed number of fat cells, and cryolipolysis permanently reduces that number in the treated area. As long as you maintain a stable weight, the results are long-lasting.</p>
 
@@ -207,7 +207,7 @@
 
         <ul>
           <li><strong>Weeks 3-4:</strong> Early changes begin as the body starts clearing dead fat cells. Some patients notice their clothes fitting slightly differently.</li>
-          <li><strong>Weeks 8-12:</strong> This is when peak results become visible. Clinical studies show an average fat reduction of 20 to 25 percent in the treated area after a single session.</li>
+          <li><strong>Weeks 8-12:</strong> This is when peak results become visible. Published results vary by treatment area, but a controlled inner-thigh trial found a single session reduced fat-layer thickness by an average of 20% on ultrasound measurement, with most patients showing some measurable reduction (Boey &amp; Wasilenchuk, 2014) — a useful benchmark, though your own result depends on the area treated, the applicator used, and your baseline fat thickness.</li>
           <li><strong>Up to 6 months:</strong> Results continue to improve as the lymphatic system completes its work. The final contour is typically evident by this point.</li>
         </ul>
 
@@ -233,9 +233,9 @@
 
         <p>Cryolipolysis has an excellent safety profile. It is FDA-cleared, non-invasive, and requires zero downtime. The technology has been refined over more than a decade of clinical use worldwide.</p>
 
-        <p>Common side effects are mild and temporary: redness at the treatment site, localised numbness or tingling, and occasionally mild bruising. These typically resolve within a few days to two weeks.</p>
+        <p>Common side effects are mild and temporary: redness at the treatment site, localised numbness or tingling, and occasionally mild bruising. These typically resolve within a few days to two weeks — consistent with a retrospective chart review of over 2,700 treatment cycles that recorded no serious adverse events and only a handful of cases of mild, self-resolving pain (Stevens et al., 2013).</p>
 
-        <p>A rare side effect known as paradoxical adipose hyperplasia (PAH) -- where the treated area increases in size rather than decreasing -- has been documented in a very small percentage of cases. While uncommon, it is important that patients are aware of this possibility, which is why I discuss it during every consultation.</p>
+        <p>A rare side effect known as paradoxical adipose hyperplasia (PAH) -- where the treated area increases in size rather than decreasing -- has been documented in a very small percentage of cases; the original case series estimated an incidence around 0.005% of treatment cycles at the time (Jalian et al., 2014). While uncommon, it is important that patients are aware of this possibility, which is why I discuss it during every consultation. For a fuller breakdown of PAH incidence and other safety data, see our <a href="/blog/cryolipolysis-safety-fda-clinical-data">complete review of cryolipolysis safety and clinical trial data</a>.</p>
 
         <p>At OPAL Radiant, all cryolipolysis procedures are performed under my direct supervision. I use only certified, medical-grade equipment and follow strict clinical protocols to ensure the highest standard of safety and efficacy.</p>
 
@@ -253,6 +253,17 @@
 
         <p>The best way to determine if cryolipolysis is right for you is a one-on-one consultation. At OPAL Radiant, I offer complimentary body assessments where we evaluate your concerns, discuss realistic outcomes, and design a treatment plan tailored to your goals. <a href="/book-appointment">Book your free consultation today</a> and find out what fat freezing can do for you.</p>
 
