diff --git a/blog/hifu-everything-you-need-to-know.html b/blog/hifu-everything-you-need-to-know.html
index fd5a6d1..50549fc 100644
--- a/blog/hifu-everything-you-need-to-know.html
+++ b/blog/hifu-everything-you-need-to-know.html
@@ -206,7 +206,7 @@
 <p>HIFU (High-Intensity Focused Ultrasound) is one of the most requested non-surgical face-lift treatments today. But it's also misunderstood. Here's what every candidate should know before booking.</p>
 
 <h2>What HIFU Actually Is</h2>
-<p>HIFU delivers focused ultrasound energy deep into the skin — reaching depths of 1.5mm, 3mm and 4.5mm — where new collagen is triggered. Over 3 months, that new collagen firms and lifts the treated area. No cuts. No injections. No downtime.</p>
+<p>HIFU delivers focused ultrasound energy deep into the skin — reaching depths of 1.5mm, 3mm and 4.5mm, targeting the same subdermal and superficial muscular aponeurotic system layer addressed in surgical facelifts — producing controlled thermal injury that triggers collagen denaturation and subsequent new collagen formation at each programmed depth (MacGregor &amp; Tanzi, 2013). Energy-based devices that heat tissue above roughly 42°C are understood to stimulate fibroblasts to produce more collagen, which is the shared mechanism behind HIFU and related skin-tightening technologies (Fritz &amp; Salavastru, 2016). Preclinical research on focused-ultrasound devices has documented increased collagen types I and III and elastin, alongside lower levels of the enzymes that normally break collagen down, supporting this mechanism at the tissue level (Kwack &amp; Lee, 2023). As that new collagen matures, it firms and lifts the treated area. No cuts. No injections. No downtime.</p>
 
 <h2>What HIFU Treats</h2>
 <p>Best for: mild-to-moderate skin laxity on the jawline, cheeks, brow, neck, and décolletage. Also excellent as a preventive treatment for women in their 30s starting to see early laxity.</p>
@@ -218,13 +218,13 @@
 <p>30–60 minutes, depending on treatment area. You'll feel warm tingling and mild "pressure" as ultrasound is delivered. Some points feel more sensitive than others — a cooling gel keeps skin comfortable. No numbing usually needed, though some clinics apply topical anaesthetic.</p>
 
 <h2>Right After the Session</h2>
-<p>You may see slight redness for a few hours. No downtime — you can return to work, go for dinner, apply makeup. Some patients notice mild "tenderness" to touch for 24–48 hours.</p>
+<p>You may see slight redness for a few hours. No downtime — you can return to work, go for dinner, apply makeup. Some patients notice mild "tenderness" to touch for a day or two afterward — a pattern consistent with HIFU studies on other body areas, which report transient redness, swelling, and tenderness lasting up to around ten days as the most common side effects, with no lasting complications at follow-up (Asiran Serdar &amp; Tukenmez Demirci, 2020).</p>
 
 <h2>When You See Results</h2>
-<p>Very subtle tightening in the first 2 weeks. Peak lifting between 6 weeks and 3 months as new collagen forms. Full effect visible by 3 months.</p>
+<p>Very subtle tightening in the first 2 weeks. Peak lifting typically develops over the following weeks to months as new collagen forms and remodels — this progressive, delayed-onset pattern is consistent with how microfocused ultrasound is understood to work, producing a deeper wound-healing response and collagen remodeling that builds gradually rather than immediately (MacGregor &amp; Tanzi, 2013).</p>
 
 <h2>How Long HIFU Lasts</h2>
-<p>12–18 months for most women. Annual maintenance sessions sustain the lift. HIFU results are cumulative — each year's session builds on the previous.</p>
+<p>Many women report the lift holding for roughly a year, with some seeing benefit for longer; exact duration varies by individual skin quality, ongoing collagen turnover, and natural ageing, so we treat published ranges as a general guide rather than a guarantee. Annual maintenance sessions help sustain the lift, and results are generally considered cumulative — each session building on the collagen remodeling from the last.</p>
 
 <h2>HIFU vs Other Options</h2>
 <p>Vs surgical facelift: less dramatic, no downtime, non-invasive. Vs thread lift: safer, more subtle, longer-lasting. Vs Botox/fillers: HIFU addresses skin laxity, while Botox smooths and fillers add volume. Often combined. See our <a href="/compare/hifu-vs-thread-lift">HIFU vs Thread Lift comparison</a>.</p>
@@ -241,6 +241,17 @@
 
