diff --git a/blog/how-to-prepare-for-first-laser-hair-removal-session.html b/blog/how-to-prepare-for-first-laser-hair-removal-session.html
index 0a2ac6b..5c07a79 100644
--- a/blog/how-to-prepare-for-first-laser-hair-removal-session.html
+++ b/blog/how-to-prepare-for-first-laser-hair-removal-session.html
@@ -209,10 +209,10 @@
 <p>Stop waxing, threading, plucking or epilating the area you plan to treat. These methods remove hair from the root, which the laser needs to target. Shaving is fine — you must actually shave regularly during this window.</p>
 
 <h2>2 Weeks Before</h2>
-<p>Avoid sun exposure, tanning beds, and self-tanners on the treatment area. Tanned or sunburnt skin has a higher risk of pigment changes or burns during laser. If you must be outdoors, apply SPF 50+ broad-spectrum sunscreen.</p>
+<p>Avoid sun exposure, tanning beds, and self-tanners on the treatment area. Tanned or sunburnt skin has a meaningfully higher risk of pigment changes or burns during laser — in a review of documented laser and IPL treatment errors, roughly one in five cases involved a patient with darker or more tanned skin being treated without adjusting for it, and pigmentation changes were by far the most common resulting complication (Hammes et al., 2012). If you must be outdoors, apply SPF 50+ broad-spectrum sunscreen.</p>
 
 <h2>1 Week Before</h2>
-<p>Discontinue any retinoids, retinol, or exfoliating acids (glycolic, salicylic) on the treatment area. These can make skin more sensitive. Also avoid strong actives like hydroquinone or benzoyl peroxide.</p>
+<p>Discontinue any retinoids, retinol, or exfoliating acids (glycolic, salicylic) on the treatment area — these are well established to increase skin sensitivity and irritation, so as a precaution we recommend a break before any energy-based treatment. Also avoid strong actives like hydroquinone or benzoyl peroxide.</p>
 
 <h2>24 Hours Before</h2>
 <p>Shave the treatment area with a clean, sharp razor. Do not wax or thread. Clean the skin — no lotions, oils, or deodorant on treatment day.</p>
@@ -221,14 +221,23 @@
 <p>Wear loose, comfortable clothing. Do not apply makeup, deodorant, perfume or lotion on the area. Bring water. Arrive 10–15 minutes early for consultation and any patch test.</p>
 
 <h2>What to Expect</h2>
-<p>For your first session, we'll do a patch test on a small area to confirm the laser settings are safe for your skin type. This adds only 10–15 minutes. Then the full session follows — anywhere from 15 minutes (upper lip) to 90 minutes (full body).</p>
+<p>For your first session, we'll do a patch test on a small area to confirm the laser settings are safe for your skin type. Individualised settings matter here: published long-term studies on diode laser hair removal report good safety and hair-reduction outcomes across skin types, including darkly pigmented skin, specifically when energy and handpiece settings are matched to the individual rather than fixed (Ross, Ibrahimi &amp; Kilmer, 2018). The patch test adds only 10–15 minutes. Then the full session follows — anywhere from 15 minutes (upper lip) to 90 minutes (full body).</p>
 
 <h2>After Your First Session</h2>
-<p>Skin may be slightly red or warm for a few hours. Apply the cooling gel we provide. Avoid hot showers, saunas, swimming, sun exposure and heavy workouts for 24–48 hours. Use SPF 50+ religiously for the next 2 weeks.</p>
+<p>Skin may be slightly red or warm for a few hours — mild-to-moderate redness and swelling right after treatment is the most commonly reported immediate response in published diode laser studies, not a sign anything went wrong (Ross, Ibrahimi &amp; Kilmer, 2018). Apply the cooling gel we provide. Avoid hot showers, saunas, swimming, sun exposure and heavy workouts for 24–48 hours. Use SPF 50+ religiously for the next 2 weeks.</p>
 
 
         </div>
 
