diff --git a/blog/laser-hair-removal-aftercare.html b/blog/laser-hair-removal-aftercare.html
index 6f468f6..4416932 100644
--- a/blog/laser-hair-removal-aftercare.html
+++ b/blog/laser-hair-removal-aftercare.html
@@ -206,7 +206,7 @@
 <p>What you do in the 48 hours and 4 weeks after your laser session significantly affects your results. Good aftercare speeds up results, reduces side effects, and prevents complications. Here is what I tell every patient.</p>
 
 <h2>Immediately After the Session</h2>
-<p>You'll see mild redness and possibly slight swelling around the hair follicles — this is normal and settles within a few hours. The area may feel warm, like mild sunburn. Apply the aloe or cooling gel we provide.</p>
+<p>You'll see mild redness and possibly slight swelling around the hair follicles — this is the most commonly reported immediate response in published diode laser studies, not a sign anything went wrong, and it settles within a few hours (Ross, Ibrahimi &amp; Kilmer, 2018). The area may feel warm, like mild sunburn. Apply the aloe or cooling gel we provide.</p>
 
 <h2>First 24–48 Hours</h2>
 <p>Avoid: hot showers, saunas, hammams, hot yoga, swimming pools, sea water, and heavy sweat-inducing workouts. Warm water is fine. Cool compresses can help with any lingering warmth.</p>
@@ -215,7 +215,7 @@
 <p>This is when sun protection matters most. Apply broad-spectrum SPF 50+ religiously on the treated area, even indoors near windows. Avoid direct sun and tanning. Skip retinoids, glycolic acid, and strong exfoliants.</p>
 
 <h2>Between Sessions</h2>
-<p>Do NOT wax, thread, pluck, or epilate. You must only shave between sessions. This is because the laser targets hair in the growth cycle, which requires the follicle to be intact.</p>
+<p>Do NOT wax, thread, pluck, or epilate. You must only shave between sessions. This is because the laser targets hair in the growth cycle, which requires the follicle to be intact — and separately, shaving is simply gentler on skin that has just been treated: a controlled study measuring inflammatory skin markers found that plucking and waxing produced significantly more erythema than shaving in the same post-removal window (Evans et al., 2020), which is exactly the kind of extra irritation you want to avoid between sessions.</p>
 
 <h2>What About the Hair "Coming Back"?</h2>
 <p>You'll notice hair "growing" in the days after your session — this is actually the treated hair shedding out. It falls out over 1–3 weeks. Genuine regrowth from active follicles takes 4–6 weeks.</p>
@@ -224,14 +224,24 @@
 <p>The treated area may be more sun-sensitive than normal for 2 weeks. Use physical sunscreen (zinc/titanium oxide) if you have sensitive skin.</p>
 
 <h2>Speeding Up Results</h2>
-<p>Consistency is everything. Attend all sessions on schedule (4–6 weeks apart). Track hair growth with photos. Stay hydrated. A healthy diet supports skin recovery.</p>
+<p>Consistency is everything. Attend all sessions on schedule — published treatment protocols space sessions 4 to 6 weeks apart over a course of 6-7 sessions, the interval associated with meaningful hair-count reduction by six-month follow-up (Ross, Ibrahimi &amp; Kilmer, 2018). Track hair growth with photos. Stay hydrated. A healthy diet supports skin recovery.</p>
 
 <h2>When to Call the Clinic</h2>
-<p>Call us if you experience: blistering, severe swelling that doesn't settle, unusual dark or light patches lasting more than a week, or any pain or infection signs. These are rare but treatable when caught early.</p>
+<p>Call us if you experience: blistering, severe swelling that doesn't settle, unusual dark or light patches lasting more than a week, or any pain or infection signs. These are rare but treatable when caught early — and the laser-safety literature is fairly consistent on why they happen at all: a review of documented laser and IPL treatment errors found the leading causes were excessive energy settings, the wrong device for the skin type, treating tanned or darker skin without adjustment, and inadequate cooling (Hammes et al., 2012). It's exactly why equipment, calibrated settings, and dermatologist supervision matter as much after your session as during it.</p>
 
 
