diff --git a/blog/laser-hair-removal-for-pcos.html b/blog/laser-hair-removal-for-pcos.html
index 4fcf7c2..d71d48d 100644
--- a/blog/laser-hair-removal-for-pcos.html
+++ b/blog/laser-hair-removal-for-pcos.html
@@ -203,16 +203,16 @@
         </figure>
 
         <div class="blog-post__content">
-<p>PCOS (Polycystic Ovary Syndrome) affects roughly 1 in 5 Indian women. One of its most distressing effects is hirsutism — excess coarse hair on the face, chin, chest, stomach and back. As a dermatologist, I see this concern almost daily. Here's the honest truth about managing PCOS hair with laser.</p>
+<p>PCOS (Polycystic Ovary Syndrome) is one of the most common hormonal conditions affecting Indian women of reproductive age — Indian population studies report prevalence ranging from roughly 4% in general screening to over 20% in clinic-referred groups, depending on the diagnostic criteria used and who is being screened (Deswal et al., 2019). One of its most distressing effects is hirsutism — excess coarse hair on the face, chin, chest, stomach and back. As a dermatologist, I see this concern almost daily. Here's the honest truth about managing PCOS hair with laser.</p>
 
 <h2>Why PCOS Causes Excess Hair</h2>
-<p>PCOS elevates androgens (male-pattern hormones). These activate hair follicles in "male-pattern" areas — face, chest, stomach — turning fine hairs into coarse, dark ones. Waxing and threading damage the skin without addressing the underlying activation.</p>
+<p>PCOS elevates androgens (male-pattern hormones), which play a central role in hair growth, differentiation, and distribution (Karn et al., 2014). These activate hair follicles in "male-pattern" areas — face, chest, stomach — turning fine hairs into coarse, dark ones. Waxing and threading damage the skin without addressing the underlying hormonal activation.</p>
 
 <h2>How Laser Helps</h2>
 <p>Laser hair removal permanently reduces hair by destroying active follicles. For PCOS, this works — but the protocol is different from standard laser courses. You need more sessions, and you need ongoing maintenance because PCOS keeps activating new follicles over time.</p>
 
 <h2>The PCOS Laser Protocol</h2>
-<p>Instead of the standard 6–8 sessions, most PCOS patients need 8–12 sessions to reduce visible hair to comfortable levels. After the initial course, expect maintenance sessions every 3–6 months for years — sometimes indefinitely, depending on how well PCOS is managed medically.</p>
+<p>Instead of the standard 6–8 sessions, most PCOS patients need 8–12 sessions to reduce visible hair to comfortable levels. This lines up with clinical data: patients with high androgen levels needed an average of 8.1 Nd:YAG laser sessions for substantial hair reduction, compared with 5.7 sessions for patients with normal hormone levels (Karn et al., 2014), and a comparative trial found PCOS-related hirsutism responded less completely than idiopathic hirsutism to the same six-session Nd:YAG course, because the underlying hormonal imbalance keeps activating new follicles (Nabi et al., 2021). After the initial course, expect maintenance sessions every 3–6 months for years — sometimes indefinitely, depending on how well PCOS is managed medically.</p>
 
 <h2>Combine Laser with Medical Management</h2>
 <p>Laser alone treats the visible hair. It doesn't fix the hormonal driver. Best results come from combining laser with proper PCOS management — through diet, exercise, and any medications your endocrinologist prescribes. This slows follicle activation and reduces the maintenance sessions needed.</p>
@@ -221,10 +221,10 @@
 <p>Laser targets dark, coarse hair — the kind PCOS produces. It doesn't work well on fine peach fuzz or blonde/grey hair. If you have those, additional treatments like MNRF or electrolysis may be needed for a small subset of hairs.</p>
 
 <h2>The Emotional Side</h2>
-<p>Many PCOS patients feel ashamed of their hair — often after years of dealing with it. A women-only clinic environment matters. So does having a dermatologist who understands PCOS and doesn't rush your treatment.</p>
+<p>Many PCOS patients feel ashamed of their hair — often after years of dealing with it. This isn't just a cosmetic complaint: a clinical trial of laser-assisted hair removal in hirsute women found measurable improvements in both depression scores and quality-of-life indices as visible hair reduced (Hosseini et al., 2022). A women-only clinic environment matters. So does having a dermatologist who understands PCOS and doesn't rush your treatment.</p>
 
 <h2>Realistic Expectations</h2>
-<p>Laser will dramatically reduce your hair — often 70–90% permanent reduction. But it can't promise "zero maintenance" for PCOS, because new follicles can activate. The right frame: laser turns a monthly threading appointment into a maintenance session once every few months.</p>
+<p>Laser meaningfully and durably reduces hair growth over a full course of treatment. The exact percentage varies by study, device, and — importantly — by whether the hirsutism is PCOS-driven or idiopathic: PCOS-related hirsutism has been shown to respond less completely and less durably to laser than hirsutism from other causes, because ongoing hormonal activity keeps recruiting new follicles (Nabi et al., 2021). It can't promise "zero maintenance" for PCOS. The right frame: laser turns a monthly threading appointment into a maintenance session once every few months.</p>
 
 <h2>When to Start</h2>
 <p>The earlier you start, the better. Younger patients respond faster because the follicles are less "established". Also, treating hair while your PCOS is well-managed medically gives the best long-term outcome.</p>
