diff --git a/blog/q-switched-laser-truth.html b/blog/q-switched-laser-truth.html
index dfd9158..6dda576 100644
--- a/blog/q-switched-laser-truth.html
+++ b/blog/q-switched-laser-truth.html
@@ -209,13 +209,13 @@
 <p>"Q-Switched" refers to the ultra-short pulse duration. Instead of gently heating the skin, Q-Switched lasers deliver energy in nanosecond bursts — powerful enough to shatter pigment particles without damaging surrounding tissue.</p>
 
 <h2>Why It's Safer for Indian Skin</h2>
-<p>Traditional continuous-wave lasers heat skin, which triggers pigment in darker skin. Q-Switched lasers avoid heating because the pulse is too short. This makes them one of the few laser types truly safe for Fitzpatrick IV–V (Indian skin).</p>
+<p>Traditional continuous-wave lasers heat skin, which triggers pigment in darker skin. Q-Switched lasers avoid sustained heating because the pulse is too short. This is part of why Q-Switched Nd:YAG is favoured for Fitzpatrick IV–V (Indian skin) in the consensus recommendations published by the Pigmentary Disorders Society and South Asian Pigmentary Disorders Forum — though that same expert panel is careful to note that laser is not first-line therapy for melasma and should be reserved as an adjuvant in resistant cases, with careful patient selection and counselling, given the risk of worsening pigmentation if used incorrectly (Sarkar et al., 2017).</p>
 
 <h2>What Q-Switched Treats</h2>
 <p><strong>Melasma</strong> — at very low fluences, it lightens deep pigment gently. <strong>Sun spots and freckles</strong> — targeted destruction of superficial pigment. <strong>Tattoo removal</strong> — shatters ink particles for the body to clear. <strong>Carbon laser facial</strong> — combines with carbon paste for pore refinement and glow.</p>
 
 <h2>The Key: Correct Fluence</h2>
-<p>For Indian skin, fluence (energy level) matters more than anything. Too high causes burns, blistering, and paradoxical darkening. Too low is ineffective. The right fluence delivers safe progressive lightening over 4–8 sessions.</p>
+<p>For Indian skin, fluence (energy level) matters more than anything. Too high causes burns, blistering, and paradoxical darkening. Too low is ineffective. The right fluence delivers safe progressive lightening over a course of sessions — a study of Q-Switched 1064nm Nd:YAG laser toning for melasma found that consistent sunscreen use during treatment significantly improved outcomes, while pre-existing photoaging and hormonal factors were linked to poorer improvement, underlining how much aftercare and patient factors (not just the laser settings) determine the result (Rivera et al., 2019).</p>
 
 <h2>What to Expect</h2>
 <p>Session lasts 15–30 minutes. Skin feels warm and mildly stingy. Immediately after: mild redness. Over the next 2 weeks: gradual pigment fading. Multiple sessions build the effect.</p>
@@ -224,7 +224,7 @@
 <p>Some clinics use Q-Switched at high fluences for "fast" results. This is dangerous on Indian skin. Others use IPL and call it "laser". Always ask what specific laser system is used — Q-Switched Nd:YAG is the answer for Indian skin.</p>
 
 <h2>Realistic Timelines</h2>
-<p>Melasma: 6+ sessions over 3+ months for substantial improvement. Ongoing maintenance needed. Sun spots: 2–4 sessions for clearance. Tattoo removal: 6–12 sessions over a year.</p>
+<p>Melasma: 6+ sessions over 3+ months for substantial improvement. Ongoing maintenance needed. Sun spots: 2–4 sessions for clearance. Tattoo removal: typically 6–12 sessions over a year for professional tattoos, though this varies considerably with ink density and technique — amateur tattoos generally clear faster than professional ones because the ink sits closer to the skin surface, and multi-pass session techniques have been shown to speed clearance compared with a single pass per session (Abbas et al., 2021).</p>
 
 <h2>Combining Q-Switched with Other Treatments</h2>
 <p>Best results come from combining Q-Switched with strict sun protection, prescription topical brighteners, and periodic <a href="/services/chemical-peel">chemical peels</a>. As a stand-alone treatment, results are slower.</p>
