diff --git a/blog/signs-laser-hair-removal-is-working.html b/blog/signs-laser-hair-removal-is-working.html
index dd85a82..ebb339e 100644
--- a/blog/signs-laser-hair-removal-is-working.html
+++ b/blog/signs-laser-hair-removal-is-working.html
@@ -206,25 +206,25 @@
 <p>One of the most common questions I hear from patients: "How do I know it's working?" Laser hair removal doesn't give instant results — the effects build over sessions. Here are the five signs your treatment is on track.</p>
 
 <h2>1. Hair Shedding in the First Weeks</h2>
-<p>After each session, treated hair sheds over 1–3 weeks. You'll notice hair falling out in the shower or when you rub the skin gently. This is proof the laser destroyed the follicle bond.</p>
+<p>After each session, treated hair typically sheds over the following 1–3 weeks. You'll notice hair falling out in the shower or when you rub the skin gently. This shedding reflects the laser's underlying mechanism — selective photothermolysis, in which heat absorbed by melanin in the follicle disables the targeted hair follicle (Thomas &amp; Houreld, 2019).</p>
 
 <h2>2. Slower Regrowth</h2>
-<p>After session 1, you'll notice hair takes longer to reappear — perhaps 4–5 weeks instead of the usual 2–3. By session 3–4, this stretches to 6–8 weeks or longer.</p>
+<p>After session 1, many patients notice hair takes longer to reappear than before treatment. By session 3–4, the hair-free interval often stretches out further still — a pattern consistent with published laser hair removal studies, which document the hair-free interval lengthening progressively across a course of sessions (McGill et al., 2007).</p>
 
 <h2>3. Finer, Softer Hair</h2>
-<p>When hair regrows between sessions, it comes back finer, softer, and lighter. What was once coarse and dark now feels almost like peach fuzz.</p>
+<p>When hair regrows between sessions, it typically comes back finer, softer, and lighter — a change in hair caliber and pigmentation that's consistently reported in long-term laser hair removal studies (Eremia et al., 2001). What was once coarse and dark now feels almost like peach fuzz.</p>
 
 <h2>4. Patchy Regrowth</h2>
-<p>Instead of hair growing back evenly, it becomes patchy — some areas remain smooth while others have sparse regrowth. This shows the laser is progressively eliminating follicles.</p>
+<p>Instead of hair growing back evenly, it becomes patchy — some areas remain smooth while others have sparse regrowth. This reflects the underlying biology: a laser session only disables follicles that were in the active growth (anagen) phase at that time, so different follicles are caught on different cycles from one session to the next (Thomas &amp; Houreld, 2019).</p>
 
 <h2>5. Less Discomfort in Each Session</h2>
 <p>The first session is often the most sensation-heavy because there's the most active hair to treat. By sessions 3–4, most women describe treatments as noticeably more comfortable — fewer follicles to react.</p>
 
 <h2>When You Won't See Big Changes</h2>
-<p>Session 1 and 2 sometimes feel "underwhelming" because hair growth cycles vary. Only 20–30% of your hair is in the active growth phase at any time — so each session targets that portion. This is why 6–8 sessions are needed.</p>
+<p>Session 1 and 2 sometimes feel "underwhelming" because hair growth cycles vary. Only a portion of your hair — commonly estimated at roughly a fifth to a third — is in the active growth phase at any given time, and each session can only treat that portion (Thomas &amp; Houreld, 2019). This is why 6–8 sessions are needed.</p>
 
 <h2>The 6-Month Mark</h2>
-<p>By the end of a full course (6–8 sessions), most patients see 80–95% permanent reduction. What remains is usually very fine, sparse hair — easily managed with occasional maintenance.</p>
+<p>By the end of a full course (6–8 sessions), most patients see a substantial, long-lasting reduction in hair. Published long-term studies on comparable lasers report results commonly in the 60–80% range, varying by skin type, hair colour, and device (Eremia et al., 2001). What remains is usually very fine, sparse hair — easily managed with occasional maintenance.</p>
 
 <h2>Photos Help</h2>
 <p>The best way to track progress? Take a photo before every session, in the same lighting. Comparing session 1 to session 6 makes the change dramatic.</p>
