diff --git a/blog/under-eye-dark-circles-treatments.html b/blog/under-eye-dark-circles-treatments.html
index a74e705..065017c 100644
--- a/blog/under-eye-dark-circles-treatments.html
+++ b/blog/under-eye-dark-circles-treatments.html
@@ -206,16 +206,16 @@
 <p>Under-eye dark circles are one of the most searched skin concerns in India. But the treatment depends entirely on the cause — and most patients don't know what type they have. Here's a dermatologist's ranking of what works.</p>
 
 <h2>First, Identify the Type</h2>
-<p>There are four main types of under-eye darkness: <strong>pigmented</strong> (brown melanin), <strong>vascular</strong> (blue/purple from visible blood vessels), <strong>structural</strong> (hollowing casts a shadow), and <strong>mixed</strong> (most common in Indian skin). Each type needs a different treatment.</p>
+<p>There are four main types of under-eye darkness: <strong>pigmented</strong> (brown melanin), <strong>vascular</strong> (blue/purple from visible blood vessels), <strong>structural</strong> (hollowing casts a shadow), and <strong>mixed</strong> (most common in Indian skin). Each type needs a different treatment — a framework echoed in published dermatology reviews of periorbital hyperpigmentation, which group its causes into pigmentary, vascular, structural, and mixed categories (Sarkar et al., 2016; Michelle et al., 2021).</p>
 
 <h2>For Pigmented Dark Circles</h2>
-<p>Best: prescription-strength topicals (hydroquinone, kojic acid, niacinamide, vitamin C) plus targeted <a href="/services/chemical-peel">chemical peels</a>. Q-Switched Nd:YAG laser can help for stubborn pigment. Timeline: 3–6 months for visible improvement.</p>
+<p>Best: prescription-strength topicals (hydroquinone, kojic acid, niacinamide, vitamin C) plus targeted <a href="/services/chemical-peel">chemical peels</a>. Q-Switched Nd:YAG laser can help for stubborn pigment — a fractional, low-fluence 1064 nm Q-switched Nd:YAG laser given over six sessions produced statistically significant reductions in melanin index and improved skin lightness in one clinical trial (Alavi et al., 2022), though results with other laser wavelengths on pigmented dark circles have been more inconsistent, with some carrying a real risk of worsening pigmentation rather than improving it (AlRamthan et al., 2024). Timeline: 3–6 months for visible improvement.</p>
 
 <h2>For Vascular Dark Circles</h2>
 <p>Best: caffeine-based topicals (temporary), tissue-tightening treatments to hide vessels, and adequate sleep. In some cases, dermal fillers to add volume and hide the vascular tint. Long-term: healthy circulation, sleep, and hydration matter most.</p>
 
 <h2>For Structural Dark Circles (Hollowing)</h2>
-<p>Best: dermal fillers (hyaluronic acid) to restore lost volume in the tear trough. <a href="/services/hifu-face-lift">HIFU or MNRF</a> can help with mild laxity. Fillers give the most dramatic results but require expert placement.</p>
+<p>Best: dermal fillers (hyaluronic acid) to restore lost volume in the tear trough. <a href="/services/hifu-face-lift">HIFU or MNRF</a> can help with mild laxity. Fillers can give the most dramatic results, but the infraorbital area's thin skin and complex anatomy make it prone to side effects — bruising, swelling, and bluish discoloration when filler sits too superficially or is overfilled — which is why published clinical guidance emphasizes correct technique, layer-specific placement, and expert injection in this area (Siperstein, 2022).</p>
 
 <h2>For Mixed Dark Circles (Most Common)</h2>
 <p>Best: combination approach — topicals + peels + fillers as needed. A dermatologist assessment is essential to determine what proportion is pigment vs vascular vs structural.</p>
@@ -232,6 +232,18 @@
 
