diff --git a/blog/understanding-melasma.html b/blog/understanding-melasma.html
index 1d43dc9..ba97db0 100644
--- a/blog/understanding-melasma.html
+++ b/blog/understanding-melasma.html
@@ -206,10 +206,10 @@
 <p>Melasma is one of the most common skin concerns I see — brown or grey-brown patches on the cheeks, forehead, upper lip or jawline. It's also one of the most frustrating, because it's chronic. Here's what every patient with melasma should understand.</p>
 
 <h2>What Melasma Actually Is</h2>
-<p>Melasma is deep, symmetric pigmentation triggered by hormones and sunlight. It affects women far more than men, especially in the 20–40 age range. Indian skin (Fitzpatrick IV–V) is particularly prone to it.</p>
+<p>Melasma is a chronic, acquired form of hypermelanosis — symmetric, irregularly bordered brown-to-grey-brown patches, typically on the cheeks, forehead, upper lip or jawline (Handel et al., 2014). It affects women far more than men, especially in the 20–40 age range. Indian skin (Fitzpatrick IV–V) is particularly prone to it.</p>
 
 <h2>The Real Causes</h2>
-<p>Melasma is triggered by hormones (pregnancy — hence the name "mask of pregnancy" — birth control, hormonal IUDs), UV light, heat, blue light from screens, and inflammation from skincare products. Genetics play a role too.</p>
+<p>Melasma is triggered by hormones (pregnancy — hence the name "mask of pregnancy" — birth control, hormonal IUDs), UV light, heat, blue light from screens, and inflammation from skincare products. Pregnancy is one of the most consistent hormonal triggers: a global survey of 324 women with melasma found 26% reported onset during pregnancy and 42% reported onset in the months after delivery (Ortonne et al., 2009). Genetics play a role too — over 40% of patients in published case series report an affected first-degree relative (Handel et al., 2014).</p>
 
 <h2>Why It's So Stubborn</h2>
 <p>Melasma isn't on the skin surface. The pigment sits in deeper layers, which is why creams alone rarely fix it. And because hormones and sunlight keep triggering new pigment, treatment doesn't "cure" melasma — it manages it.</p>
@@ -218,7 +218,7 @@
 <p>This is non-negotiable. Broad-spectrum SPF 50+ every single day, reapplied every 3 hours. Also blue-light-blocking sunscreens for the hours you're on screens. Without this, no other treatment will work.</p>
 
 <h2>Step 2: Topical Brightening</h2>
-<p>Prescription-strength topicals: hydroquinone, tretinoin, kojic acid, azelaic acid, niacinamide. These reduce pigment production and speed cell turnover. Compounded formulas often work better than off-the-shelf products for Indian skin.</p>
+<p>Prescription-strength topicals: hydroquinone — the most-studied and most effective single pigment-lightening agent for melasma in clinical trial reviews (Gupta et al., 2006) — along with tretinoin, kojic acid, azelaic acid, and niacinamide. These reduce pigment production and speed cell turnover. Compounded formulas often work better than off-the-shelf products for Indian skin. Anyone who is pregnant or breastfeeding should discuss timing with a dermatologist first — some of these actives, including oral and topical retinoids, carry separate pregnancy-specific precautions covered in our <a href="/blog/melasma-in-pregnancy-chloasma">melasma-in-pregnancy guide</a> (Chien et al., 2016).</p>
 
 <h2>Step 3: In-Clinic Treatments</h2>
 <p>For deeper melasma, we combine topical care with in-clinic <a href="/services/chemical-peel">chemical peels</a> (glycolic, TCA), <a href="/services/carbon-laser-facial">Q-Switched Nd:YAG laser</a> at low fluences (never high — high settings can worsen melasma), and occasionally microneedling.</p>
